A prevalent surrogate for NPP is the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI) (Xu et al., 2011), calculated from data in the red and near-infrared parts of the electromagnetic spectrum. Trends.Earth, bi-weekly MODIS and AVHRR products are utilized to compute annual integrals of NDVI. The trajectory metric gauges the pace of primary productivity changes over time. By conducting a pixel-level linear regression, Trends.Earth identifies areas witnessing shifts in primary productivity during the studied period. A positively significant trend in NDVI may indicate a potential enhancement in land condition, possibly resulting from improved soil moisture, better nutrient availability, or successful land management practices. In areas previously affected by degradation, such as deforestation, overgrazing, or drought, a positive NDVI trend signifies vegetation recovery and regeneration. while a negative significant trend could signal degradation potential, often caused by factors like water scarcity, soil degradation, deforestation and intensive agriculture (Huang et al., 2020). Upon aggregation, this sub-indicator yield a five-class classification: Improving, Stable, Stable but Stressed, and Early Signs of Declining [Fig. 3
                           ] (Sims et al., 2021). Improving category represents land areas where productivity is increasing over time, land with consistent and unchanging productivity falls into Stable category, Stable but Stressed class is land that remains stable but exhibits signs of stress, Early Signs of Declining class shows land with early indications of decline in productivity, and Declining represents land with a clear reduction in productivity.


3.1.2 Land cover

The evaluation of alterations in land cover necessitates the availability of land cover maps encompassing the study area for both the baseline and target years. These maps should possess an acceptable level of accuracy and be constructed in a manner conducive to credible comparisons (Strahler et al., 2006). While Trends.Earth employs the ESA CCI land cover maps as the default dataset, local maps can also be incorporated. In this particular study, we utilized the United Nations initiative on Global Geo-spatial Information Management's Land Cover Datasets, with a 30Â m resolution [Fig. 4
                           ], spanning from the year 2001 to 2020 improving the final outcomes for SDG 15.3.1 indicator [Fig. 5
                           ].

Drawing from localized insights into the conditions within the study area and the ongoing land degradation processes there, we can employ a land cover change matrix [Table 2
                           ]. This matrix serves to identify transitions that correspond to degradation (â), improvement (+), or the absence of change in terms of land condition (0) (Sims et al., 2021). In our specific scenario, we modified the default value for grassland (which includes shurbs and sparsely vegetated areas) to denote degradation (â). This adjustment is warranted since Chinese environmental authorities categorize the transformation of grassland into cropland as land degradation, as this transition entails altering the original natural land cover into an artificial one (RodrÃ­guez et al., 2016).


